---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I find out what my Brisbane home is worth?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The most accurate method is a comparative market appraisal from an agent who actively works your suburb. They assess recent sales of genuinely comparable properties, your home's condition and presentation, and current buyer demand at your price point. Online estimates from automated tools are often 10 to 20% off because they cannot account for these variables."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are online property valuations accurate in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Automated valuations (such as those from Domain or CoreLogic) use recent sales data but cannot assess your property's specific condition, renovation quality, aspect, street appeal, or the nuances of your street versus the suburb average. They are useful as a starting point but should not be relied on for pricing decisions."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What factors affect property value in Brisbane's inner east?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Key drivers in Brisbane's inner east include school catchment (particularly state primary zones), land size and usability, proximity to the river or parkland, the quality of renovation if carried out, street presentation, flood overlay status, and the level of buyer competition for that property type in that suburb at that moment."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I get a free property appraisal in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most real estate agents offer free appraisals. For an appraisal that is genuinely useful rather than just a number designed to win your business, choose an agent who has demonstrable recent sales in your suburb. Ask them to walk through the comparable sales they are using and to give you a realistic range with the reasoning behind it."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout title="How Much Is My Home Worth in Brisbane? | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Online property estimates are often unreliable. Here's what actually determines the value of a Brisbane home, and how to get an accurate read on what yours could achieve." schema={faqSchema}>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        ← All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers · 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How Much Is My Home Worth in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Online estimates can be wildly inaccurate. Here's what actually determines your property's value, and how to get an honest number you can act on.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The question of what a Brisbane home is worth comes up constantly, and the answer is almost never as simple as typing an address into a property portal. Automated estimates are a useful starting point for casual curiosity, but they have real limitations that matter when you are making decisions about selling, refinancing, or estate planning. Understanding what actually drives value gives you a far more reliable basis for those decisions than any algorithm can.</p>

      <p>Property value in Brisbane's inner and middle suburbs is determined by a combination of land, location, and the specific attributes of the dwelling. These factors interact in ways that are often highly localised and that automated tools consistently struggle to capture. A house in Hawthorne and a structurally similar house two streets over can differ by $200,000 simply because of aspect, flood risk, proximity to the river, or the orientation of the back yard relative to the afternoon sun. No algorithm has access to that level of granular, on-the-ground knowledge.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why online estimates are often unreliable</h2>
      <p>Automated valuation models work by comparing recent sales within a defined radius and applying statistical adjustments for size, bedrooms, and bathrooms. The problem is that Brisbane's inner-east suburbs are highly heterogeneous. A 405m2 block in Norman Park backing onto a gully is not comparable to a 405m2 block on a ridge line with city views. A post-war home in original condition and a fully renovated home on the same street are not the same asset. Automated tools do not know which of those two situations applies to your property, and the adjustments they make for condition and features are crude at best.</p>

      <p>The other structural problem is data lag. Automated valuations rely on settled sales, which in Queensland typically means the data is two to four months behind the contract date. In a moving market, that lag produces estimates that are systematically out of date. When conditions are shifting, the gap between an automated estimate and what a well-run campaign would actually achieve can be substantial.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Land size and configuration</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner and middle rings, land is the primary driver of value. The dwelling sitting on it matters, but in most established suburbs the land makes up the majority of the total asset value. A larger allotment, particularly one with a wide frontage and workable dimensions, commands a premium because it gives buyers optionality: the ability to extend, rebuild, or develop over time.</p>

      <p>Configuration matters as much as raw size. A 600m2 block with a regular rectangular shape and rear lane access is worth meaningfully more than a 600m2 block that is irregular, steeply sloping, or constrained by an easement. Corner blocks are valued differently again, partly for the street presence and partly because they typically offer better access for future development. When comparing your land against recent sales to get a sense of value, use blocks that are genuinely comparable in both size and configuration, not just size.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Aspect and orientation</h2>
      <p>Aspect is one of the most underappreciated drivers of value in Brisbane, and one of the factors automated tools handle worst. North-facing back yards are consistently sought after in Queensland because they maximise usable outdoor living in the afternoon when families are actually home. A north-facing rear aspect means the pool, deck, or garden is in sun through the cooler months and shaded by the house in summer. Buyers who have lived through a south-facing back yard in Brisbane know exactly what they are looking for and will pay accordingly.</p>

      <p>Views, particularly river views or city skyline views, also carry premiums that are difficult to quantify with general comparable sales data. The premium varies by angle, permanence, and how much of the view is actually captured from the living areas. A partial glimpse of the river from an upstairs bedroom is worth something; an unobstructed panoramic river view from the main living level is worth considerably more. Getting this right requires someone who has been inside the comparable properties, not just seen their sale prices.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Renovation quality and presentation</h2>
      <p>Not all renovation is equal, and buyers in Brisbane's inner-east market are generally sophisticated enough to distinguish between work that has been done properly and work that looks good in photographs but has not addressed the structural or functional fundamentals. A kitchen that photographs beautifully but has no storage, poor layout, or cheap finishes will be discounted by experienced buyers. Conversely, a renovation that gets the layout, materials, and functionality right adds enduring value.</p>

      <p>The areas that typically deliver the strongest return are kitchens, bathrooms, outdoor living spaces, and the overall presentation and condition of the property. Structural work that removes constraints, such as opening up a ground floor or adding a functional parent's retreat, tends to be valued more highly than cosmetic work that simply refreshes the surface. As a rule, buyers pay most for things they would not want to do themselves after purchase. If your renovation removes the big ticket items from their mental checklist, it adds real value to your price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How comparable sales actually work</h2>
      <p>A properly constructed comparable sales analysis selects recent sales of properties that are genuinely similar to yours in location, land configuration, dwelling type, and overall condition. The skill is in the selection and the adjustments. Using a sale from a different street that sits in a flood zone when your property does not is not a valid comparable. Using a sale from a home in original condition to estimate the value of a fully renovated home without a material adjustment is not valid either.</p>

      <p>The most reliable comparable sales are recent, within the same suburb or an immediately adjacent one with a similar price profile, and similar enough in their key attributes that the adjustments required are modest. Three to five good comparables give you a defensible range. The spread of that range tells you something useful: a tight range means the market is pricing properties like yours consistently; a wide range means there is significant variation in buyer response and the specific attributes of your property and campaign will have a larger influence on the outcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a proper appraisal involves</h2>
      <p>A genuine market appraisal is a detailed assessment of your property against current comparable sales, conducted by an agent who has inspected the property in person and understands the specific market conditions operating in your suburb right now. It should give you a realistic price range, an honest assessment of what presentation or preparation would make a material difference to that range, and a clear explanation of the comparable sales the estimate is based on.</p>

      <p>It is not a number plucked from a database. It is not a figure designed to make you feel good so you sign an agency agreement. A useful appraisal is one you can interrogate, where the agent can explain exactly which sales they used, why, and what adjustments were made. If an agent cannot walk you through their reasoning clearly and specifically, the number they have given you is not worth much.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Want to know what your home is actually worth?</strong> Daniel provides honest, data-led appraisals grounded in real comparable sales and direct knowledge of Brisbane's inner-east market. No inflated numbers, no obligation. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Book a free appraisal.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>
</Layout>
